and so various explanatory schemes are built.

25:26.500 --> 25:36.500
The Rotor is widely known as a person who has the concept of the locus of control.

25:36.500 --> 25:38.500
As for the locus of control,

25:38.500 --> 25:44.500
it is another characteristic of the needs that a person has.

25:45.500 --> 25:50.500
It is a generalized expectation.

25:50.500 --> 25:54.500
Remember the expectation as a variable

25:54.500 --> 25:57.500
with which we analyze social interaction.

25:57.500 --> 26:01.500
The locus of control is a generalized expectation

26:01.500 --> 26:08.500
of the extent to which people are able to control and reinforce their lives.

26:08.500 --> 26:10.500
A person is an active being,

26:10.500 --> 26:16.500
and a person builds on the basis of the operative reinforcement of the skinner.

26:16.500 --> 26:26.500
A person builds his behavior from the point of view of the analysis of the consequences that arise here.

26:26.500 --> 26:30.500
The Rotor introduces the category of the locus of control,

26:30.500 --> 26:35.500
and it introduces it precisely so that it is possible to measure expectations.

26:35.500 --> 26:38.500
It creates a questionnaire on the locus of control

26:39.500 --> 26:45.500
and, accordingly, its task is to measure such a subjective thing as expectations.

26:45.500 --> 26:47.500
And it succeeds.

26:47.500 --> 26:50.500
From the point of view of the Rotor,

26:50.500 --> 26:54.500
which has conducted a large number of experiments,

26:54.500 --> 26:57.500
conducted a factor analysis of its data,

26:57.500 --> 27:02.500
it turned out that the whole large community of people

27:02.500 --> 27:05.500
with their abundance of internal variables,

27:05.500 --> 27:09.500
immersed in the abundance of external stimuli,

27:09.500 --> 27:12.500
can be divided into two categories.

27:12.500 --> 27:16.500
These are externals and internals.

27:18.500 --> 27:21.500
Again, as for the Rotor,

27:21.500 --> 27:24.500
its concept of locus of control

27:24.500 --> 27:33.500
is very much in line with the concept of Jung's introverts-extroverts.

27:34.500 --> 27:39.500
However, if for Jung, from the point of view of behaviorists,

27:39.500 --> 27:43.500
these are very poorly measurable concepts,

27:43.500 --> 27:47.500
then instead of these concepts, introverts-extroverts,

27:47.500 --> 27:55.500
the Rotor will be measurable from the point of view of behaviorism,

27:55.500 --> 27:58.500
the concept of externals and internals.

27:58.500 --> 28:03.500
An external is a person who assumes

28:03.500 --> 28:11.500
that the control over his reaction, behavior, and expectations lies outside.

28:11.500 --> 28:18.500
External stimuli are dominant from the point of view of determining any achievements,

28:18.500 --> 28:21.500
and little depends on a person.

28:22.500 --> 28:30.500
External is a typical object of Skinner's study.

28:30.500 --> 28:34.500
A person who has abandoned internal activity,

28:34.500 --> 28:38.500
is under the influence of external stimuli.

28:38.500 --> 28:42.500
Internals are quite the opposite.

28:42.500 --> 28:49.500
Internals are those people whose locus of control is inside them.

28:49.500 --> 28:56.500
They are those people who pay a lot of attention to their internal variables.

28:56.500 --> 29:05.500
All external stimuli that act on them are analyzed, processed by internal variables,

29:05.500 --> 29:08.500
and go through an internal cognitive map.

29:08.500 --> 29:11.500
Only after this analysis,

29:11.500 --> 29:18.500
only after the analysis of possible consequences of different behavioral variants,

29:18.500 --> 29:21.500
only in this case,

29:21.500 --> 29:26.500
the variant that suits a person is chosen.

29:26.500 --> 29:32.500
If externals are the people by external circumstances,

29:32.500 --> 29:37.500
then internals are the people by their cognitive circumstances.

29:38.500 --> 29:42.500
As for the concept of locus of control,

29:42.500 --> 29:48.500
it had a significant impact on the whole cognitive-behavioral direction,

29:48.500 --> 29:56.500
because it allowed to build a scale of expectations,

29:56.500 --> 30:01.500
with pluses of external and internal.

30:02.500 --> 30:08.500
Again, we should pay attention to the fact that there are no pure externals.

30:08.500 --> 30:13.500
If a person is mentally healthy, then there are no pure externals and pure internals.

30:13.500 --> 30:16.500
There are no people who are in the locus of control.

30:16.500 --> 30:20.500
Someone is completely dependent on external circumstances,

30:20.500 --> 30:23.500
someone makes decisions on their own.

30:23.500 --> 30:26.500
Even if we take a newborn child,

30:26.500 --> 30:29.500
who seems to be completely dependent on external influence,

30:29.500 --> 30:38.500
he still quickly forms his needs, his interests, his desires.

30:38.500 --> 30:41.500
He smiles to someone, he cries to someone.

30:41.500 --> 30:49.500
Thus, he starts to let all these external factors through the inner world.

30:49.500 --> 30:56.500
And he achieves the desired reaction in normal situations by this crying.

30:57.500 --> 31:00.500
Again, there are no pure externals,

31:00.500 --> 31:08.500
because no mentally healthy person will be immersed in his own thinking.

31:08.500 --> 31:12.500
Just because if you have an 8-hour working day,

31:12.500 --> 31:16.500
and you come and start to think about what you should do at work today,

31:16.500 --> 31:18.500
you will think for a day, two, three.

31:18.500 --> 31:22.500
Then you will be asked, what did you do in the past week?

31:22.500 --> 31:24.500
And then you will have the following conclusions.

31:25.500 --> 31:29.500
People are on this scale.

31:29.500 --> 31:33.500
They are closer to the external end, closer to the internal end.

31:33.500 --> 31:39.500
They have priority behaviors, priority ways of reacting.

31:39.500 --> 31:43.500
And as for these priority behaviors and reactions,

31:43.500 --> 31:51.500
they determine our behavior, our expectations,

31:51.500 --> 31:54.500
they determine our dominance, our status,

31:54.500 --> 31:56.500
they determine the value of our support,

31:56.500 --> 32:02.500
and they make possible the prediction of the potential of our behavior.

32:02.500 --> 32:09.500
This is what concerns the cognitive-behavioral approach

32:09.500 --> 32:14.500
and the direction that was developed by Rotor.

32:15.500 --> 32:24.500
These are the main directions that exist in the theory of learning from the behavioral point of view.

32:24.500 --> 32:29.500
But we see that starting from radical behaviorism,

32:29.500 --> 32:31.500
from the stimulus reaction,

32:31.500 --> 32:35.500
gradually the same behaviorism more and more

32:35.500 --> 32:38.500
takes into account the internal qualities,

32:38.500 --> 32:41.500
the internal properties, the internal needs of a person.

32:41.500 --> 32:42.500
Motives, needs.

32:42.500 --> 32:50.500
It doesn't matter that behaviorists formulate them in an unusual psychological way.

32:50.500 --> 32:56.500
Moreover, they formulate them in a way that there is an opportunity to measure the corresponding results.

32:56.500 --> 33:05.500
But behaviorists, solving the original task of explanation, analysis, measurement,

33:05.500 --> 33:07.500
control of human behavior,

33:07.500 --> 33:15.500
come to the conclusion that if we want to solve the task of prediction of human behavior,

33:15.500 --> 33:18.500
we must take into account the internal variables,

33:18.500 --> 33:20.500
that is, the internal world of a person.

33:20.500 --> 33:31.500
And, of course, reality itself leads them to the recognition of the human mental activity.

33:32.500 --> 33:35.500
But as for the mental activity of a person,

33:35.500 --> 33:38.500
which they left from initially,

33:38.500 --> 33:40.500
because Otson, creating behaviorism,

33:40.500 --> 33:46.500
was principally distancing himself from the psyche until scientists themselves understood it.

33:46.500 --> 33:49.500
Well, if they didn't understand it, we will study behavior.

33:49.500 --> 33:55.500
About 50 years after the emergence of behaviorism,

33:55.500 --> 34:00.500
behaviorism, in fact, came close to the cognitive direction,

34:00.500 --> 34:09.500
which is associated with the ideas of how a person lives, how a person thinks.

34:09.500 --> 34:12.500
As for the cognitive approach,

34:12.500 --> 34:17.500
the representatives of this direction come from one simple thing.

34:17.500 --> 34:23.500
Yes, behaviorists, moreover, as well as any other cognitiveist,

34:23.500 --> 34:30.500
psychologist, they are in solidarity with behaviorists in terms of measurability,

34:30.500 --> 34:33.500
in terms of experimentality.

34:33.500 --> 34:38.500
But the representatives of the cognitive direction come from the fact that

34:38.500 --> 34:43.500
the unconditional difference between a person and all other animals

34:44.500 --> 34:53.500
is that a person possesses a wide range of developed cognitive abilities.

34:53.500 --> 34:58.500
A person is capable of thinking, a person is capable of thinking,

34:58.500 --> 35:01.500
a person is capable of solving abstract problems.

35:01.500 --> 35:04.500
The same animals can solve problems,

35:04.500 --> 35:09.500
and monkeys, dogs, rats, mice,

35:10.500 --> 35:14.500
they also solve the problem of finding food,

35:14.500 --> 35:21.500
they can solve the problem of saving and moving according to their norms.

35:21.500 --> 35:25.500
But as for a person, unlike all other, in any case,

35:25.500 --> 35:28.500
currently known animals,

35:28.500 --> 35:32.500
only a person has a cognitive structure,

35:32.500 --> 35:37.500
with which a person is able to transmit his inner feelings,

35:37.500 --> 35:41.500
his vision of the world, his perception of the world to another person.

35:41.500 --> 35:44.500
A person has speech, he has a notion.

35:44.500 --> 35:49.500
Due to the existence of this cognitive structure,

35:49.500 --> 35:56.500
a person is able to think, to know the world,

35:56.500 --> 36:04.500
and to know this world is considerably deeper than a person needs for his survival.

36:05.500 --> 36:09.500
Indeed, what concerns the knowledge of the world,

36:09.500 --> 36:12.500
which was inherent in our ancestors 50-100 thousand years ago,

36:12.500 --> 36:15.500
it was more than enough for them to survive,

36:15.500 --> 36:19.500
simply because, since we exist, this proves it.

36:19.500 --> 36:25.500
A person is perfectly able to provide conditions for his existence,

36:25.500 --> 36:29.500
survival, and from this point of view,

36:29.500 --> 36:32.500
he is adequately adapted to reality.

36:32.500 --> 36:36.500
But as for a person,

36:36.500 --> 36:42.500
his thinking has spread to those spheres of reality,

36:42.500 --> 36:47.500
which are not directly connected with his survival.

36:47.500 --> 36:52.500
Let's take the universe, let's take the micro-world.

36:52.500 --> 36:55.500
Of course, this can be interesting.

36:55.500 --> 36:59.500
But not everyone understands the laws of quantum mechanics in the micro-world,

36:59.500 --> 37:02.500
and the laws of quantum mechanics in the mega-world,

37:02.500 --> 37:04.500
the theory of relativity.

37:04.500 --> 37:09.500
But, for the duration of our lives, 50, 70, 100, 150 years,

37:09.500 --> 37:12.500
none of us will fall into the micro-world,

37:12.500 --> 37:15.500
none of us will be in other universes.

37:15.500 --> 37:17.500
This is an excess of knowledge.

37:17.500 --> 37:20.500
But a person is engaged in this knowledge,

37:20.500 --> 37:24.500
a person devotes time to this knowledge,

37:24.500 --> 37:27.500
this knowledge is socially demanded.

37:27.500 --> 37:29.500
Why is it needed?

37:29.500 --> 37:33.500
And the cognitivists set and solve this problem.

37:33.500 --> 37:39.500
A person has thinking, a person has cognitive mechanisms.

37:39.500 --> 37:43.500
And since they exist, they are needed for some reason.

37:43.500 --> 37:46.500
Nature is very simple.

37:46.500 --> 37:51.500
All excess qualities and properties that are not used,

37:51.500 --> 37:54.500
are taken away and disappear.

37:54.500 --> 37:58.500
If the thinking of a person has not disappeared,

37:58.500 --> 38:06.500
and it is pleasant to realize and it is believed that it is increasing and deepening,

38:06.500 --> 38:08.500
although this is a controversial question,

38:08.500 --> 38:12.500
then, accordingly, let's start from the fact that

38:12.500 --> 38:16.500
cognition, cognitive properties, cognitive functions

38:16.500 --> 38:23.500
are a significant characteristic necessary for the survival and adaptation of a person.

38:23.500 --> 38:27.500
And this is the basic idea of the cognitive approach.

38:27.500 --> 38:31.500
As for the cognitive approach,

38:31.500 --> 38:38.500
from this point of view, it pays principal attention to education and learning.

38:38.500 --> 38:41.500
From the point of view of the cognitivists,

38:41.500 --> 38:44.500
a person is, in fact, a researcher,

38:44.500 --> 38:49.500
striving to understand and interpret what is happening to him in the world,

38:49.500 --> 38:52.500
what is happening in the world that surrounds him.

38:52.500 --> 38:59.500
And this is not to write a dissertation,

38:59.500 --> 39:01.500
to make any discovery,

39:01.500 --> 39:06.500
but to understand what is happening in the world from the point of view of prediction.

39:06.500 --> 39:09.500
What dangers may exist in this world?

39:09.500 --> 39:13.500
What problems may exist in this world?

39:13.500 --> 39:16.500
What conditions may exist in this world?

39:17.500 --> 39:21.500
In this regard,

39:21.500 --> 39:31.500
a person is considered as an ordinary scientist, an ordinary researcher.

39:31.500 --> 39:36.500
If I find myself in a new environment for myself,

39:36.500 --> 39:38.500
I must study it.

39:38.500 --> 39:43.500
Let's recall those situations when we find ourselves in some new room,

39:43.500 --> 39:47.500
in a new room, in a new group, when we come to a new job.

39:47.500 --> 39:49.500
Where do we start?

39:49.500 --> 39:51.500
We start by getting acquainted,

39:51.500 --> 39:54.500
learning about the rules,

39:54.500 --> 39:58.500
finding out what is approved and what is not.

39:58.500 --> 40:02.500
We explore a new environment of our stay.

40:02.500 --> 40:06.500
If we come to work, we will work there for some time,

40:06.500 --> 40:11.500
and, accordingly, we will work not alone, but with other people.

40:11.500 --> 40:14.500
We need to know the rules and norms that exist there.

40:14.500 --> 40:21.500
We need to know and be able to interpret the forms of behavior that exist there

40:21.500 --> 40:24.500
in order to be properly understood.

40:24.500 --> 40:28.500
And if, for example, someone made a mistake,

40:28.500 --> 40:32.500
and this was made known to the management,

40:32.500 --> 40:34.500
it is not a trick.

40:34.500 --> 40:40.500
It is just a normal norm of attitude in this company,

40:40.500 --> 40:45.500
because this or that mistake can have a significant impact

40:45.500 --> 40:50.500
on the final results that will be achieved in this company.

40:50.500 --> 40:53.500
So, a person is a researcher.

40:53.500 --> 40:55.500
And if a person is a researcher,

40:55.500 --> 41:03.500
all his actions, all his behavior is primarily related to acquiring new knowledge,

41:03.500 --> 41:06.500
acquiring new information.

41:06.500 --> 41:12.500
Knowledge from the point of view of fundamental physics or mathematics,

41:12.500 --> 41:15.500
knowledge in the environment where I live,

41:15.500 --> 41:19.500
where I am, knowledge in the environment where I am.

41:20.500 --> 41:24.500
The most prominent figure of the cognitive approach,

41:24.500 --> 41:27.500
in fact, one of his chiefs,

41:27.500 --> 41:30.500
was George Alexander Kelly.

41:30.500 --> 41:33.500
As for Kelly,

41:33.500 --> 41:41.500
the main idea is what is the cognitive ability of a person.

41:41.500 --> 41:46.500
The cognitive ability of a person is an organization of a cycle

41:46.500 --> 41:49.500
of orientation in the world around,

41:49.500 --> 41:54.500
the choice of possible behavior options,

41:54.500 --> 41:58.500
and, finally, the execution of one or another option.

41:58.500 --> 42:01.500
So, orientation, choice, execution.

42:01.500 --> 42:04.500
Again, in a significant way,

42:04.500 --> 42:08.500
this is intersected with the cognitive behavioral approach,

42:08.500 --> 42:10.500
when we talk about internal changes,

42:10.500 --> 42:13.500
with the bandura and the rotor, with its social environment.

42:13.500 --> 42:19.500
But if behavioralists came from external stimuli

42:19.500 --> 42:22.500
and internal stimuli, internal changes,

42:22.500 --> 42:25.500
then Kelly is basically based on the fact

42:25.500 --> 42:29.500
that a person has the ability to learn.

42:29.500 --> 42:33.500
A person is a researcher, a person learns all his life.

42:33.500 --> 42:37.500
And he learns neither at school, nor in the family, nor in kindergarten.

42:37.500 --> 42:39.500
This is one of the forms of learning.

42:39.500 --> 42:43.500
Whatever a person encounters, it is a learning.

42:43.500 --> 42:50.500
Because he must be oriented in the environment

42:50.500 --> 42:51.500
where he is.

42:51.500 --> 42:56.500
A new place, a new house, a new car,

42:56.500 --> 43:01.500
a new way of moving, skates, rollerskates, something else.

43:01.500 --> 43:04.500
I must be oriented in what it is.

43:04.500 --> 43:08.500
I must understand what dangers there may be,

43:08.500 --> 43:12.500
what are the advantages, what are the disadvantages.

43:12.500 --> 43:16.500
I must get a certain choice of options,

43:16.500 --> 43:22.500
a choice of options I need to implement those or other actions.

43:22.500 --> 43:26.500
And after I know these options,

43:26.500 --> 43:28.500
after I get oriented in them,

43:28.500 --> 43:32.500
I implement some option, I do something.

43:32.500 --> 43:36.500
And then I look, whether it was successful or not.

43:36.500 --> 43:38.500
Did I achieve what I wanted? No.

43:38.500 --> 43:43.500
But if behavioralists had consequences of behavior

43:43.500 --> 43:47.500
as the main result of solving this problem,

43:47.500 --> 43:49.500
stimulus, internal change reaction,

43:49.500 --> 43:53.500
then the principle of Kili is different.

43:53.500 --> 43:58.500
Each person has some constructs in his head,

43:58.500 --> 44:02.500
some conceptual, verbal schemes

44:02.500 --> 44:06.500
with which a person describes the world.

44:06.500 --> 44:09.500
And a person is not Skinner's rat.

44:09.500 --> 44:13.500
Skinner liked to do experiments with rats.

44:13.500 --> 44:15.500
We talked about it.

44:15.500 --> 44:19.500
In the sense that he works with his trial and error.

44:19.500 --> 44:23.500
He pressed the key, the food fell, I will press further.

44:23.500 --> 44:26.500
He stumbled somewhere, got under tension,

44:26.500 --> 44:30.500
I will not come to this place in the cage anymore.

44:30.500 --> 44:33.500
A person does not work according to the method of trial and error.

44:33.500 --> 44:40.500
A person is not so primitive to fill himself with bumps.

44:40.500 --> 44:47.500
A person works from the point of view of the picture of the world in his head.

44:47.500 --> 44:52.500
From the point of view of the knowledge he received,

44:52.500 --> 44:55.500
seeing what happened to others,

44:55.500 --> 44:58.500
what they did, what they didn't do.

44:58.500 --> 45:01.500
And then, after I am in the head,

45:01.500 --> 45:04.500
not in practice, as Bandura,

45:04.500 --> 45:06.500
from the point of view of modeling,

45:06.500 --> 45:09.500
not Rotter, from the point of view of social learning,

45:09.500 --> 45:13.500
but in the head, guided by his inner criteria,

45:13.500 --> 45:18.500
his cognitive, cognitive, his experience.

45:18.500 --> 45:25.500
Here, we can easily use all our favorite psychological terms.

45:25.500 --> 45:29.500
So, based on my inner criteria,

45:29.500 --> 45:32.500
based on my experience, my memory,

45:32.500 --> 45:38.500
only based on them, I already interpret what is happening in the world,

45:38.500 --> 45:46.500
I already choose how I will behave in this or that situation.

45:46.500 --> 45:51.500
A person is a thinker who thinks how to behave,

45:51.500 --> 45:54.500
and then he gains experience.

45:54.500 --> 45:57.500
A person is not a rat that behaves,

45:57.500 --> 46:02.500
and then he considers the loss of his body.

46:02.500 --> 46:06.500
So, this is the basic idea of the cognitive approach,

46:06.500 --> 46:12.500
which, of course, Kelly finds its expression in more specific sentences.

46:12.500 --> 46:15.500
Now we will consider these sentences.

46:15.500 --> 46:20.500
In fact, all the cognitive theories of George Alexander Kelly

46:20.500 --> 46:24.500
are the theory of building, education,

46:24.500 --> 46:28.500
the theory of learning and development of a person in general.

46:28.500 --> 46:33.500
Kelly comes from the idea of constructive alternativeism.

46:33.500 --> 46:38.500
With the help of personal constructs,

46:38.500 --> 46:40.500
a person describes reality.

46:40.500 --> 46:43.500
A personal construct is a set of terms

46:43.500 --> 46:47.500
with which I create a picture of the world.

46:47.500 --> 46:54.500
A personal construct is built on the principle of similarity and difference.

46:54.500 --> 46:56.500
It is dichotomous, double.

46:56.500 --> 47:03.500
At the same time, Kelly comes from the idea that each person has his own personal constructs,

47:03.500 --> 47:06.500
his own interpretations, his own approaches.

47:06.500 --> 47:09.500
But with the help of these constructs, a person interprets the surrounding world.

47:09.500 --> 47:13.500
The world in which he lives, where other people live,

